<ab><lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/>νος  <expan><abbr>ἐπο</abbr><ex>ί</ex><abbr>ει</abbr></expan>  </ab>
</div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p> [...] son of [...] n (perhaps Zenon), made (this)</p>
            <p>or</p>
            <p>[Kobla]nos made (it)</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>See Erim-Reynolds, loc. cit., suggesting [...] son of [...] n (perhaps Zenon), made (this). Smith considers, however, that there is no room for a name and patronymic, and prefers to see this as the end of a name in the nominative: he proposes the already known sculptor, Koblanos.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="bibliography">
            <p>Published by <bibl n="ktejmr1991">Erim-Reynolds, 'Sculptors' no.<citedRange>12</citedRange>
               </bibl>, whence <bibl n="seg">
                  <title level="j">SEG</title> 40 <citedRange>1990.935</citedRange>
               </bibl>. Published, with the bust, by <bibl n="rrrs2006">
                  <author>Smith</author>, <title>Roman Portrait Statuary from Aphrodisias</title>, no. <citedRange>110</citedRange>
               </bibl>
            </p>
         </div>
